column12: ARYLPIPERIDINE DERIVATIVES
column13: N-alkyl or oxyalkyl arylpiperidine cpds. of formula (I) are new. In (I), Ar = Ph, fluorophenyl, chlorophenyl, trifluoromethylphenyl, methoxyphenyl, tolyl or naphthyl opt. substd. with F, Cl, CF3 or OMe; n= 2-4; X= O, S or a direct bond; R= Ph, hydroxyphenyl, methoxyphenyl, tolyl, 2-amino-4-thiazolylphenyl, 5-oxindolyl, 2-methyl-4-oxo-4H-pyrido (1,2a)pyrimidin-3-yl, 7,9-dioxo-8-azaspiro(4,5)decan-8-yl or 1,8,8-trimethyl-2,4-dioxo -3-azabicyclo(3.2.1)heptan-3-yl. - Also new are arylpiperidine cpds. (II) from which (I) are prepd.. - (I) can be prepd. by reacting (II) with at least an equiv. amt. in moles of an aralkyl (or aryloxyalkyl) or heterocyclyl ether deriv. or corresp. halide of formula: Q(CH2)nXR where Q= a leaving gp. (e.g. p-toluenesulphonyloxy or halogen) in a reaction-inert polar organic solvent (partic. acetone or MIBK), under anhydrous conditions, in the presence of at least an equiv. amt of an appropriate base (partic. Na2CO3 or K2CO3). A temp. of 50-150 deg.C for 2-24 hrs. is used.

column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR CORING SUBTERRANEAN HOLES
column13: There is described a method and apparatus for nonrotatively forming holes in the ground between first and second spaced locations, the apparatus comprising a pilot hole forming head for forming a pilot hole between the first and second spaced locations, a broaching head having a first trailing end and a second leading end for cutting a core of earth, core extruders cooperating with the broaching head to extrude the core of earth, and winches respectively connected to the leading end of the broaching head for pulling the broaching head along the pilot hole towards the second location to cut the core of earth and to the trailing end of the broaching head to pull the broaching head towards the first location to extrude the core of earth.
column15: ADAM ARTHUR

column12: Schere.
column15: ADAM ARTHUR

column12: GUIDING HEAD
column13: In an apparatus for forming horizontal subterranian holes there is described a guide head for attachment to a broaching head comprising a central elongate shaft adapted at one end thereof for releasable connection to the broaching head and a plurality of radial fin members disposed about the shaft to provide directional stability during the pushing of the broaching head through the ground.
column15: ADAM ARTHUR

column12: EARTH BORING APPARATUS
column13: There is described a new and improved method and apparatus for boring subterranian holes between horizontally spaced locations, comprising a broaching head having a first trailing and a second leading end for cutting a bore hole through the ground, a rod string releasably connectible to the first end thereof for pushing the broaching head through the ground; a guiding head cooperating with the broaching head for guiding the movement of the broaching head between the horizontally spaced locations, and extruders to extrude the incised core of the bore. The broaching head is pushed between the locations to cut a core, which passes through the head, by forming first and second coaxial incisions, whereby subsequent removal of the core is facilitated.
column15: ADAM ARTHUR

column12: BROACHING HEAD
column13: In an apparatus for forming horizontal subterranian holes there is described a broaching head, comprising a central shaft, a plurality of radial ground-cutting vanes extending from the shaft, first and second circumferential ground-cutting blades spaced from and extending around the shaft and co-axial therewith, the first of said blades being disposed forwardly of the second blade, and the first circumferential groundcutting blade being spaced at a greater distance from the shaft than the second blade.
column15: ADAM ARTHUR

column12: Improvements relating to Arcuate Endless Conveyers
column13: 1,162,115. Endless conveyers. BARBER ELECTRICAL SERVICES Ltd. 14 Dec., 1967 [17 Sept., 1966; 23 Feb., 1967], Nos. 41616/66 and 8677/67. Heading B8A. An arcuate endless conveyer belt 1 in the form of a flattened truncated cone is driven over terminal rollers 2, 3 each comprised of a plurality of coaxial wheels 4 of substantially identical diameter and each wheel is rotatable about a shaft 5 independently with respect to the others. The conveyer is driven by a frustoconical drive roller 6, at the outer end of the terminal roller 2, in conjunction with a pressure roller 12. The pressure roller 12 is adjustable in pressure and position to tension the belt. A guide roller 10 attached to the drive roller has a peripheral groove to engage a guide belt 11 fitted to or formed integral with the conveyer belt 1. The guide belt 11 is also engaged by a plurality of freely rotatable guide wheels 15 spaced around the outer edge of the belt 1 between the upper and lower surfaces thereof. Rollers 17 are diametrically opposed about the rollers 15 to engage the outer surfaces of the belt and maintain the guide belt 11 in the guide wheels 15. The rollers 17 are mounted on eccentric spindles to permit adjustment of the pressure on the conveyer belt.

column12: ARYLPIPERIDINE DERIVATIVES.
column13: A SERIES OF NOVEL N-ALKYL OR OXYALKYL ARYLPIPERIDINE DERIVATIVES HAVE BEEN PREPARED, INCLUDING THEIR PHARMACEUTICALLY ACCEPTABLE ACID ADDITION SALTS, WHEREIN THE N-ALKYL OR OXYALKYL SIDE CHAIN IS FURTHER SUBSTITUTED BY CERTAIN ARYL OR HETEROCYCLIC RING GROUPS. THESE PARTICULAR COMPOUNDS ARE USEFUL IN THERAPY AS NEUROLEPTIC AGENTS FOR THE CONTROL OF VARIOUS PSYCHOTIC DISORDERS. TYPICAL AND PREFERRED MEMBER COMPOUNDS INCLUDE 4-<< 4-<2-[4-(2-METHOXYPHENYL)-1-PIPERIDINYL]ETHYL>PHENYL> > THIAZOLE-2-AMINE, 4-<<4-[4-(2-METHOXY- PHENYL)-1-PIPERIDINYL]-N-BUTYL> PHENYL> > THIAZOLE-2-AMINE, 3-<4-[4-(2-METHOXYPHENYL) -1-PIPERIDINYL]-N-BUTYL> -1, 8, 8-TRIMETHYL-3-AZABICYCLO [3.2.1] HEPTANE-2, 4-DIONE, 5-<2-[4-(2-METHOXYPHENYL)-1-PIPERIDINYL] ETHYL> OXINDOLE AND 3-<2-[4-(1-NAPHTHYL)-1-PIPERIDINYL] ETHYL > -2-METHYL-4H-PYRIDO-<1, 2-A] PYRIMIDINE-4-ONE, RESPECTIVELY. METHODS FOR PREPARING ALL THESE COMPOUNDS FROM KNOWN STARTING MATERIALS ARE PROVIDED.

column12: Improvements in or relating to gas cookers
column13: 678,222. Gas cooking stoves. MAIN, Ltd., R. & A. Oct. 24, 1950 [Sept. 12, 1949], No. 23549/49. Class 126 A gas oven has a single burner across the bottom and an outlet for the products of combustion at the top and front of the oven and an auxiliary outlet nearer or at the back of the oven. The oven is heated by a burner 10 extending across the bottom of the back wall 11. A proportion of the waste gases escape through an outlet 12 in the top wall of the oven into a flue passage 14 extending between the upper wall of the oven and the bottom wall 20 of the grill chamber. An opening in the top of flue 14 co-operates with an upwardly extending tapered flue passage 17 leading to an opening in the cooker hot-plate. Additional openings 21 in the top wall of the oven also lead to the shallow flue 14. Further openings 23, spaced apart across the top of the back wall 11 communicate with a duct 24 leading into flue passage 14. The openings 21 in the top wall may be dispensed with, and the openings 23 in the back wall may lead to a duct extending out through the cooker casing, Fig. 2 (not shown). In a modification, Fig. 3, (not shown), the additional openings in the top or back wall of the oven are replaced or supplemented by openings in the side walls near the back, which communicate with ducts leading to the shallow top flue. Alternatively or additionally openings in the side walls may lead to a duct extending out through the casing. Specification 606,576 is referred to.

column12: Improvements in or relating to gas fires
column13: 783,127. Heating air. MAIN, Ltd., R. & A. June 7, 1956 [May 25, 1955], No. 15140/55. Class 64(3) A gas fire of the kind in which burners 17 heat up refractory radiants 21 and the products of combustion are directed rearwardly to a chimney flue has a heat exchanger containing one or more passages for the products of combustion as they leave the radiants and a further passage or passages through which air from outside the gas fire is directed upwardly before flowing back into the atmosphere. The exchanger comprises a cast metal box structure having forward and rear walls 28, 26 provided on both surfaces with vertically - extending fins 33...36 and side walls 27, 29 secured together by bolts 32. Products of combustion pass through the box into a flue pipe 40 while air entering openings 47 passes upwardly between the fins 33, 36 and out into the atmosphere through openings 50. Air also enters openings 48 and recesses 43 and flows to the openings 50 via the burner chamber 9, passages 38, 37 and the space between the latter and the back plate 10 of the fire.

column12: Improvements in or relating to direct viewing storage cathode ray tube circuit arrangements
column13: 1,129,967. Cathode-ray storage tubes. MARCONI CO. Ltd. 18 March, 1966 [3 Aug., 1965], No. 33235/65. Heading H1D. In a continuously operated direct viewing storage tube, e.g. for surveillance radar, in which image decay or attenuating pulses are applied to the target backing electrode, the flood beam is pulsed to secure persistence times of e.g. 2 minutes or more. The flood beam may be physically cut-off between pulses by reducing the potential of collimating electrodes or by applying a negative potential to a spacecharge grid, or the beam may be effectively cut off by reducing still more the potential of the target backing electrode or by raising the potential of the flood gun cathode and diverting the flood beam to the collector mesh, alternate "on" pulses coinciding with the decay and viewing phases of operation. The E.H.T. applied to the screen of the tube is at a minimum during the decay phase and is at a maximum during the viewing phase. The dutyratio of the pulsed flood beam may be adjustable for brightness control and the decay pulses may comprise trains of pulses differing in duration and amplitude.

column12: IMPROVEMENTS IN AND RELATING TO COIN-OPERATED VENDING MACHINES
column13: 1,267,990. Coin operated vending machines. BARBER ELECTRICAL SERVICES Ltd. 28 March, 1969 [8 Jan., 1968], No. 52652/69. Divided out of 1,267,502. Heading G4V. In a drawer type vending machine, rapid adjusting means comprising coin separators 25, packing pieces 35, and coin replacement pieces 34 allow any combination of two coins, or alternatively a single coin, to be accepted in a coin holder 23 adapted both to receive coins on edge in the same plane and to hold said coins in the path of locking means for releasing a drawer. Coins C are received edge to edge in the holder 23 which is mounted on a bar 29. Attempts to open a drawer cause cam 29a to move the bar 29 (and hence the coins) in a plane perpendicular to the planes of the coins so as to move rollers 32 on arms 31 apart, thus releasing pawls 30 from the bar. If no coins, or coins of insufficient diameter, are present in the holder 23, the rollers pass through cut outs in the holder. To adjust the mechanism for different coins, packing pieces 35 may be inserted to accommodate smaller coins (Fig. 7) (not shown). A coin separator 25 is also used to obtain required spacing of coins (Figs. 7 and 12, not shown), and a coin replacement piece (Fig. 12) can be used if only one coin is required for the purchase. Excess coins are diverted via flap (39) (Fig. 1, not shown) and coins can be returned to the customer by pressing a button to remove a coin support 37 (Figs. 7 and 12), the coins falling down a shoot (38) (Fig. I, not shown).

column12: Improvement in, and design of, controlled guards for machine tools
column13: 1,029,807. Machinery guards. BARBER ELECTRICAL SERVICES Ltd. Aug. 17, 1964 [Nov. 23, 1963], No. 46344/63. Heading F2J. In a brake press a safety guard comprises a series of transparent spring-pressed sensors 4 arranged adjacent a press tool 2 and carried by a press bar 1, each sensor carrying an opaque signal 6 having a central hole 7 forming, with the other holes 7, a channel through which a beam of radiant energy is transmitted when the holes 7 are aligned. When one or more sensors 4 is raised with respect to the others, the beam is interrupted and causes stopping of the press. The source and receiver of the beam may be arranged in the end sensors 4 or in the frame on the machine. Electromagnetic radiation or acoustic radiation may be employed.

column12: Inertia-operated switches for motor driven vehicles
column13: 1,036,296. Inertia switches. A.C.B. CORPORATION. May 24, 1965, No. 21868/65. Heading H2B. In an inertia switch for motor vehicles the battery connection to earth is through lead 12, terminal post 11, fixed contact 15, a bell crank lever comprising moving contact arm 16 and arm 19 pivoted about pivot 18, a catch 21, feet 26 on catch 21 to housing 10. Spring 17 urges arm 16 away from contact 15, but the contacts are retained in engagement by catch 21. The contacts are broken by the energization of solenoid 31 which lifts its armature 28 to trip catch 21. In the event of a collision, steel ball 37 runs up ramp 36 and moves metal plate 38 into contact with the flaps 38a round an opening in the bottom of metal cylinder 33 connected to the battery through lead 32 thus completing the circuit between the battery and the solenoid via cylinder 33, plate 38, spring 39, post 41, washer 44 and lead 45. In the event of the vehicle overturning, steel ball 46 completes the circuit from the battery to the solenoid via cylinder 33, ball 46, disc 47, post 41, washer 44 and lead 45. The catch can be reset by bar 51 the end of which 52 engages arm 19 if the bar 51 is pulled. Bar 51 can also be used to manually energize the solenoid by pushing arm 49 carrying contact 50 against cylinder 33, arm 49 being connected by lead 48 to the solenoid.

column13: 864,963. Valve amplifier and integrator circuits. MARCONI'S WIRELESS TELEGRAPH CO. Ltd. Aug. 24, 1958 [Nov. 24, 1958], No. 37807/58. Class 40(6) [Also in Group XXXVI] An integrator comprises a vibratory capacitor 12 excited by coil 12a energised from the mains over halfwave ractifier 11 to which a unindirectional input is fed over a series resistance, the resultant alternating voltage being capacitance coupled through high gain amplifier 13 to the output through a series resistance and to one diagonal of a bridge phase sensitive rectifier 10 whose other diagonal is energised from the mains. column12: Improvements in or relating to continuous absorption refrigeration apparatus
column13: 817,839. Refrigerating. BOLINDER'S FABRIKS A. B. July 4, 1957 [July 9, 1956], No. 21254/56. Class 29 In a continuous cycle absorption refrigerating apparatus the outlet pipes from the absorber and condenser are secured in good thermal contact to the outlet pipe from the evaporator by welding, brazing or soldering. Preferably the absorber and evaporator pipes are D-shaped in crosssection with the flat faces secured together. As shown the system comprises boiler 10, rectifier 11, condenser 12, evaporator 13, absorber 15 and receiver 16. column13: A series of novel N-alkyl or oxyalkyl arylpiperidine derivatives have been prepared, including their pharmaceutically acceptable acid addition salts, wherein the N-alkyl or oxyalkyl side chain is further substituted by certain aryl or heterocyclic ring groups. Methods for preparing all these compounds from known starting materials are provided.

column12: IMPROVEMENTS IN AND RELATING TO COIN OPERATED PACKET VENDING MACHINES
column13: 1,267,502. Coin freed vending machine. BARBER ELECTRICAL SERVICES Ltd. 28 March, 1969 [8 Jan., 1968], No. 1026/68. Heading G4V. In a drawer type vending machine the lowermost article stored in a stack in magazine 1 is pushed forwards by a block 2 (Fig. 3) when the drawer is pulled out, the top of the article causing a spring loaded flap 6 to be pivoted to a horizontal position. When the article is removed from the drawer the spring returns the flap 6 to the vertical position to close off access to the remaining articles in the magazine so that further articles may not be removed illicitly by an instrument inserted through the open or partly open drawer. The flap 6 is locked in the vertical position by a hook 11 of an arm 9 engaging an extension 8 of the flap. The arm may fall under its own weight or may be spring biased. When the drawer is returned a cam 12 coacts with cam 13 of the arm 9 to raise the arm and thereby release the flap to be moved on withdrawal of the next article. The articles may be retained in the magazine by a rod (represented by line 4). When the drawer is withdrawn the remaining articles in the magazine are supported by block 2, the block also serving to obstruct access to said remaining articles. The drawer may be furnished with a cam 18 to render it compatible with the change giving mechanism of Specification 1,156,993.

column12: ANASTOMOTIC LEAKAGE DETECTION THROUGH DUAL ACTION CATHETER
column13: Technologies are generally described for detecting the presence of anastomotic leakage in the abdominal cavity through a dual action catheter placed in the vicinity of a surgery site. A portion of the dual action catheter may be affixed around the surgery site, for example, coiled around the surgery site on the intestine. Through openings on the catheter near the surgery site, a neutral fluid such as saline solution may be injected and extracted through the same openings resulting in retrieval of fluids in the same are. By testing the extracted fluids, chemical and biochemical activity within the abdominal cavity may be determined in order to gauge the start of any anastomotic leakage.
column15: ADAM QUENTIN ARTHUR CARL

column12: RIGID AND SEMI-RIGID PACKAGES
column13: A package includes first and second layers, first and second seams, panels, a fluid passage, and an end seam. A first edge of the first layer is aligned with a first edge of the second layer. A second edge of the first layer is aligned with a second edge of the second layer. The first seam connects the first edge of the first layer and the first edge of the second layer. The second seam connects the second edge of the first layer and the second edge of the second layer. The panels are defined between the first and second layers. The fluid passage is fluidly connected to the panels and enables introduction of a fluid into the panels in a form-fill-seal manufacture process. The end seam between the first seam and the second seam such that an interior volume is defined by the first layer and the second layer.

column12: INVERTED DIVERTICULUM TREATMENT DEVICES
column13: A device for treating a diverticulum includes a containment device and a bushing. The containment device includes an elongate conduit. The bushing is in the conduit of the containment device. The bushing includes a heat-shrink material. The bushing has a first tubular shape including a first open end and a second open end. At least a portion of the diverticulum in an inverted state is positionable into the first open end. The bushing is configured to transform from the first tubular shape toward a second shape upon heating the heat-shrink material. The second shape includes at least a portion of the bushing radially inward relative to the first tubular shape. The bushing in the second shape is configured to hold the diverticulum in a radially compressed inverted state.
column15: ADAM QUENTIN ARTHUR CARL

column12: Corrosion reduction for supercritical water gasification through seeded sacrificial metal
column13: Technologies are presented for reducing corrosion in supercritical water gasification through seeded sacrificial metal particles. The metal particles may be seeded into one or more material input streams through high pressure injection. Once distributed in the SCWG reactor, the metal particles may corrode preferentially to the metal SCWG reactor walls and convert into metal oxides that precipitate out above the supercritical point of water. The precipitated metal oxides may then be collected downstream of the SCWG reactor to be reprocessed back into seed metal at a smelter. The seeded metal particles may complete a process material cycle with limited net additional waste.
column15: ADAM QUENTIN ARTHUR CARL

column12: FLOW PATH IN WATER HEATER HEAT EXCHANGER PLATES
column13: A water heater heat exchanger element (800) is formed from first and second plates joined together to form at least one liquid inlet (802) and at least one liquid outlet (804), at least one channel (803, 813, 818) between the plates and interconnecting the at least one liquid inlet (802) and the at least one liquid outlet (804) to provide at least one liquid flow path inside the element (800) and a combustion heat transfer surface on the outside of the element (800), defining a combustion gas flow path that extends from a leading edge (820) to a trailing edge (822) of the element (800). The at least one liquid outlet (804) is located remote from the leading edge (820). The element (800) is further characterised by the at least one liquid flow path extending in the element (800) to direct liquid flow from the trailing edge (822) to the leading edge (820) and then closely adjacent the leading edge (820), then to connect the at least one liquid outlet (804).

column12: A hot water tank of a water heater with an inlet diffuser
column13: A vertical cylindrical storage tank for hot water comprising an inlet diffuser fitting connected to an inner end of a cold water inlet tube located at a region of discharge of cold water into a lower portion of the tank. The diffuser has plural spaced distribution openings, each smaller across its transverse axis than the diffuser inlet but in total area of openings, much larger than the diffuser inlet. The spaced openings are substantially uniform and aligned upon assembly to deliver a discrete layer of cold water within the lowest portion of the storage space. This enables incoming cold water to be dispersed from the distribution openings uniformly in plural streamline flows into the storage space below the diffuser to minimise currents that cause mixing of hot and cold water in the tank so that a greater proportion of the tank's capacity can delivered continuously at the outlet as usefully hot water.

The precipitated metal oxides may then be collected downstream of the SCWG reactor to be reprocessed back into seed metal at a smelter. The seeded metal particles may complete a process material cycle with limited net additional waste.

column12: A HOT WATER TANK OF A WATER HEATER WITH AN INLET DIFFUSER
column13: A vertical cylindrical storage tank for hot water comprising an inlet diffuser fitting connected to an inner end of a cold water inlet tube located at a region of discharge of cold water into a lower portion of the tank. The diffuser has plural spaced distribution openings, each smaller across its transverse axis than the diffuser inlet but in total area of openings, much larger than the diffuser inlet. The spaced openings are substantially uniform and aligned upon assembly to deliver a discrete layer of cold water within the lowest portion of the storage space. This enables incoming cold water to be dispersed from the distribution openings uniformly in plural streamline flows into the storage space below the diffuser to minimise currents that cause mixing of hot and cold water in the tank so that a greater proportion of the tank's capacity can delivered continuously at the outlet as usefully hot water.

column12: Validation and fast channel change for broadcast system
column13: Data service transmission from a content server to a receiver terminal using a data channel is enabled in a system in which part of the data service is transmitted using a different, broadcast channel. The broadcast channel is used to receive first data comprising part of the data service; this data is processed using a signature-generating algorithm, deriving first signature data S5.2, which is transmitted S5.3 using the data channel to the content server. The first signature data is validated S5.4 by comparison with a signature derived by processing data comprising part of the data service, using a corresponding algorithm. The terminal accesses the data service using the data channel dependent on signature validation. Also claimed is a similar dual broadcast-data channel system in which a data stream is selected, the receiver is tuned, and a message is sent to the content server, via the data channel, requesting helper data (e.g., a real-time transport protocol (RTP) burst comprising random access point (RAP) data), assisting audio visual (AV) reception. column12: THIN-FILM COATING APPARATUS FOR APPLYING ENHANCED PERFORMANCE COATINGS ON OUTDOOR SUBSTRATES
column13: A thin-film coating applicator assembly is disclosed for coating substrates in outdoor applications. The innovative thin-film coating applicator assembly is adapted to apply performance enhancement coatings on installed photovoltaic panels and glass windows in outdoor environments. The coating applicator is adapted to move along a solar panel or glass pane while applicator mechanisms deposit a uniform layer of liquid coating solution to the substrate's surface. The applicator assembly comprises a conveyance means disposed on a frame. Further disclosed are innovative applicator heads that comprise a deformable sponge-like core surrounded by a microporous layer. The structure, when in contact with a substrate surface, deposits a uniform layer of coating solution over a large surface.

column12: Method of making thermally-broken extruded frames for windows and glass doors
column13: The present invention relates to games for use on windows and glass doors and methods of making same, and particularly, methods of making a thermally broken window or door frame made from two frame members that are connected by an insulating member. Existing methods of making thermally broken hollow frame members from two frame members either are complex and time consuming and complex or present difficulties in aligning the two frame members prior to pouring the thermal barrier material. The present invention provides the use of a guide to hold the frame members and am elastomersic gasket which forces the frame members tightly inot the guide and seals the liquid-receiving channel. The frame members can then be inverted in the guide and the process repeated to produce a hollow thermally broken frame.
column15: CAMERON ARTHUR B;;MARCK ADAM T

column12: Device for diluting boiler flue gas with air
column13: Flue gas from a boiler is diluted with air in a device comprising a chamber 8 which communicates with a flue gas inlet 4, an air inlet 2 and a mixed gas outlet 6. A fan 10 is situated within an inner cylinder 12 arranged coaxially inside chamber 8. Weir gaps 15, 17 are provided to enhance the mixing of input gases. The weir gaps are formed by rings 14, 16 having an arcuate radial cross-section. In use air from inlet 2 is drawn through the inner cylinder 12 by the fan 10. Flue gas from inlet 4 is fed into chamber 8 where an upstream portion is drawn into weir gap 15 and mixed with air in cylinder 12, the downstream portion of the flue gas passing into weir gap 17 for mixing with the flue gas/air mixture. <IMAGE>

column12: Method of treating the surfaces of high carbon steel bodies and bodies of high carbon steel.
column13: A method of developing compressive residual stresses in the surface region of a high carbon steel alloy composed of 0.8 -1.6% carbon, 0.2 - 5% chromium, and 0- 20%alloying ingredients selected from the group consisting of manganese, vanadium, molybdenum, tungsten, silicon, the remainder being iron; e.g. SAE 52100 steel, comprises heating said article to a temperature of 800-950°C (1472 - 1742°F) for 1 - 2.5 hours in a carburizing atmosphere effective to generate a differential in retained austenite, primary carbides and carbon between the surface region and core region of said article; and immersing said article in a cooling medium to quench the central core of said article at a rate sufficiently fast to effectively suppress the formation of non-martensitic austenite decomposition products, thereby establishing a residual compressive stress gradient proceeding from the surface region of said article to a depth between 0.007 - 0.03 inches, the residual compressive stress being in the range of 5 - 40 Ksi. The article may be tempered thereafter.

column13: 670,407. Cooking-ovens. MAIN, Ltd., R. & A. Oct. 10, 1949 [Sept. 9, 1948], No. 21671/ 50. Class 126 (Divided out of 670,328). A grill chamber 49 and an oven 21 are arranged within the cooker casing formed from sheet metal panels having flanged edges. Hot gases leave the oven 21 through an opening 42 and pass into a shallow tray 38 which is secured to the central part of the top wall 22 of the oven 21 and which is provided with a cover 41. Hot gases pass through an opening 43 in the rear of the tray 38 into an upwardly extending conduit 44, which is disposed between the rear of the grill chamber and the outer casing of the cooker and escape through an aperture in the hot plate frame 49 of the cooker. The heat-responsive element of a thermostat is arranged within the tray 38. A splash guard 62 may be secured to the rear of the cooker. Specification 670,328 is referred to.

column12: Improvements in cooking ovens
column13: 1,118,372. Gas cooking ovens; controlling burners. R. & A. MAIN Ltd. 7 April, 1966, No. 15692/66. Headings F4T and F4W. The temperature of a cooking oven, heated by a gas burner 1, is controlled by a thermostat 18 which keeps the temperature in the range 150-550‹ F. for cooking and in the range 750- 950‹ F. for heat-cleaning of the oven walls. Waste gases pass through an opening 19 and duct 20 into a secondary duct 22 lined with refractory material 23 and heated to incandescence by a burner 25 disposed in an opening 24. The incandescent refractory 23 oxidizes the waste gases which then pass, through an opening 26, into an outlet duct 27, downstream of a Venturi constriction, so that cold air supplied by a fan 29 extracts and cools the cleaned gases. Gas supplied to burners 1 and 25 is regulated by a governor 44 and by mercury valves 37 and 38 actuated by pilot lights 33 and 34 acting on heat sensitive elements 35 and 35 respectively, glow coils 39 and 40 being used to ignite the pilot lights. The control system is such that either burner 1 alone, or burners 1 and 25 operate simultaneously, these conditions being achieved by using the appropriate setting on the oven control clock 45 and thermostat 18, the latter determining which glow coils and solenoid valves 31 and 32 are energized, these valves regulating the gass supply to the pilot lights. A heat-sensitive switch 42 closes at a pre-set temperature thus locking the oven door by causing a solenoid-operated bolt 43 to be shot.

column12: Improvements in or relating to flue controls for gas fires
column13: 977,673. Flue control relating to gas fires. R. & A. MAIN Ltd. Nov. 6, 1963 [Nov. 23, 1962], No. 44473/62. Heading F4W. A gas fire of the type wherein secondary combustion air is drawn to the burners through the fire casing bottom and diluent room air is drawn through further fire casing openings to a space within the casing, both streams flowing to an outlet at the back of the casing, is provided with chamber disposed between the casing and the flue, said chamber having upper and lower openings 18 and 19 communicating with said outlet and space respectively and a valvecontrolled flue outlet 24. The chamber comprises vertical progressively stepped rear walls 15, 16, 17 and side walls 13 attached to the fire casing by flanged edges 14. An upper flue outlet 24 and an additional lower outlet 20 are provided in the upper rear walls, the former being controlled by a flap valve 23 pivoted at 22 between the side walls and biased inwardly open by an attached weight 29. The lower edge of the outlet 24, formed by an arcuate lip 25 struck about the pivot axis, extends horizontal and parallel with the valve edge 28 until as indicated in Fig. 1 (not shown), it terminates in a cut-away inclined section 27. The outlet may be otherwise shaped but still such that the rate of decrease of outlet area decreases with valve closure. The opening 20 may be dispensed with, its equivalent flow area being provided by a clearance between the valve 23 and opening 24. If a heat exchanger is incorporated, the lower opening 19 communicates with room air through an additional opening in the fire casing.

column12: Thin-film coating apparatus for applying enhanced performance coatings on outdoor substrates
column13: A thin-film coating applicator assembly is disclosed for coating substrates in outdoor applications. The innovative thin-film coating applicator assembly is adapted to apply performance enhancement coatings on installed photovoltaic panels and glass windows in outdoor environments. The coating applicator is adapted to move along a solar panel or glass pane while applicator mechanisms deposit a uniform layer of liquid coating solution to the substrate's surface. The applicator assembly comprises a conveyance means disposed on a frame. Further disclosed are innovative applicator heads that comprise a deformable sponge-like core surrounded by a microporous layer. The structure, when in contact with a substrate surface, deposits a uniform layer of coating solution over a large surface.

column13: 670,328. Gas cookers. MAIN, Ltd., R. & A. Oct. 10, 1949 [Sept. 9, 1948], No. 23743/48. Class 126. Waste gases from the oven pass through openings 42 at the top into a covered tray 39 into which projects the heat-responsive element 46 of a thermostat, the controlling knob 93 of which is arranged outside the front wall 54 of a grill chamber 49. Waste gases pass upwardly through openings 43 in the rear of the cover of the tray 39 and through a conduit 44 at the rear of the cooker to an outlet at the top of the cooker. A splash guard 62 is attached to the rear of the cooker. The oven door 66 is formed from a pressed metal sheet flanged to fit over a cast frame, a flanged sheet-metal lining being provided. Adjustable screws 100 pass through the strips 38 and abut the ends of the flexible strips 78 so that the level of the cooker can be adjusted. A panel 83 closing an opening in the front of the base 7 may be removed by swinging it into a horizontal position and sliding it into the opening on a runner 90. Specification 670,407 is referred to.

column12: Improvements in or relating to gas ring burners
column13: 681,812. Stoves. MAIN, Ltd., R. & A. Sept. 5, 1950 [June 5, 1949], No. 12058/49. Class 126 [Also in Group XVII] A separator for the products of combustion from a gas-ring having sets of holes round both inner and outer sides of the burner tube comprises means for separating the products of combustion from the inner ring of holes and passing them clear of the products of combustion from the outer set of holes. As shown, the separator is formed as a pot support mounted above the gas ring of a cooker. The support comprises a baffle ring 10 of larger diameter than the gas ring 11 disposed above and separated from the gas ring 11. Four archshaped baffle walls 12 are supported on ring 10 within a counter-sunk portion of a cooker top-plate so that the upper edges of the walls 12 project above the top-plate and the diverging limbs of baffles 12 project beyond the ring 10. The inner burner holes 17 are located within the space bounded by the crests of arches 12 and the combustion products of these burners are led through the combustion products of the outer burner holes 16 by conduits 19 formed by the diverging limbs of the arches. The outer burner holes 16 lie within the spaces between the arch-shaped baffles 12 and the baffle ring 10. The limbs of the baffle walls 12 may terminate at ring 10, additional radial baffles being provided extending outwardly from the ring symmetrically with respect to the limbs of the baffle walls, or only one limb of the baffle walls may extend beyond ring 10. The arch-shaped baffle walls may be formed integrally with the burner, when the ring 10 is unnnecessary, or the baffle walls may be formed integral with the bottom of a utensil

column12: THERMALLY-BROKEN EXTRUDED FRAMES FOR WINDOWS AND GLASS DOORS
column13: The present invention relates to frames for use on windows and glass doors and methods of making same, and particularly, methods of making a thermally broken window or door frame made from two frame members that are connected by an insulating member. Existing methods of making thermally broken hollow frame members from two frame members either are complex and time consuming and complex or present difficulties in aligning the two frame members prior to pouring the thermal barrier material. The present invention provides the use of a guide to hold the frame members and am elastomersic gasket which forces the frame members tightly inot the guide and seals the liquid-receiving channel. The frame members can then be inverted in the guide and the process repeated to produce a hollow thermally broken frame.

column12: Improvements in or relating to gas cookers having burner igniters
column13: 986,541. Igniting gas burners. R. & A. MAIN Ltd. Sept. 4, 1963 [Nov. 7, 1962], No. 42139/62. Heading F4F. The oven burner 10 of a gas cooker is supplied with gas by a manually operated valve (not shown) and is ignited by a gas jet 26 controlled by a valve 23 and ignited by an electric filament 27, the valve 23 and a switch for energizing the filament being actuated by a push rod 18. A similar gas jet is adapted to ignite the high level grill burner. The push rod 18 extends through a plate 16 in the front of the cooker and is only accessible when the oven door 15 is open. The inner end of the push rod abuts a push button 22 on the end of the reciprocable stem of the valve 23. A head on the end of the stem is adapted to co-operate with a rubber O-ring disposed in an opening between gas inlet and outlet chambers. The switch comprises a contact strip having one end secured to an insulating block; the other end is slotted and straddles the valve stem and is adapted to make contact with the push button 22 on the valve stem when the stem is pushed inwardly to open the valve. The filament may be catalytic and is energized by a battery in a casing 28 secured to the underside of the cooker casing. The push rod for actuating the gas jet of the high level grill extends through the upright back plate on which the grill is supported and the filament is energized by the same battery as energizes the filament of the gas jet for the oven burner.

column12: Improvements in or relating to direct viewing storage tubes
column13: 1,144,590. Cathode - ray storage tubes. ENGLISH ELECTRIC VALVE CO. Ltd. 26 Oct., 1967 [30 Nov., 1966], No. 53679/66. Heading H1D. In a direct-viewing storage tube comprising writing and flood guns and a perforated storage electrode, the storage electrode includes a conductive layer divided into a plurality of mutually insulated independent portions or areas, e.g. in the form of parallel strips, having their own connections so that a selected portion only of the whole charge image may be erased. The storage electrode comprises a metal mesh 5A on which is evaporated, in succession, a thin dielectric layer 5B, a metal layer 51 subdivided into strips by evaporation through a mask, and a layer of secondary emitting dielectric 5C. A voltage may be applied between the metal layer and the metal mesh to burn out any pin holes in the interposed dielectric layer. All the layers are foraminate having e.g. 250 meshes per inch.

column12: Broadcast application security
column13: Application metadata received by a broadcast receiver S201 through a broadcast stream can be validated by obtaining a result of a comparison S202 between a reference hash and a hash of the application metadata. The application metadata is validated in response to the obtained result indicating that the reference hash matches the hash of the application metadata S203. If the obtained result does not indicate a match then: an alert may be provided to a user; user approval may be requested to launch the application; or the application may be launched in protected mode. In some embodiments, the hash of the application metadata can be generated, and/or compared to the reference hash, remotely at a server. The hash of the application metadata may be compared to a plurality of reference hashes, where each reference hash is stored with associated validity information defining a time period in which that reference has is valid. These validation methods and systems may improve broadcast security and ensure that application metadata originated from the broadcast provider as opposed to a third party such as a man-in-the-middle (MITM) attacker.

column12: Clinical syringe with electrical stimulation aspects
column13: A treatment device is provided for applying electrical energy to biological tissue in conjunction with injecting a composition that advantageously diffuses through the tissue. An injector such as a syringe has a reservoir for the treatment composition and injection cannula. The cannula can function as an electrode, and one or more additional electrodes are provided as opposed electrodes. The electrodes can each have tissue penetrating needles, or one or more of the electrodes can have a surface bearing conductive contact part. The syringe or other injector and a drive unit that applies electrical power to the electrodes are operable simultaneously or in a sequence, and can be triggered by switches or automatically upon detection of the injection proceeding to a predetermined state. The treatment device preferably uses a disposable syringe received in a carrier and generally is provided with a non-threatening appearance by minimizing tissue penetration and potential high voltage aspects.

column12: Receiving a broadcast stream
column13: An apparatus and method for receiving a broadcast stream is provided. The apparatus is configured to receive key information and additional information through the broadcast stream, select one of a plurality of predetermined functions based on the additional information, and perform the selected function in response to a control signal identified by the key information. The additional information may include link information such as a URL or telephone number, and the function may be selected based on a type of the link information. In some embodiments, the link information may be extracted from audio-visual data of a selected programme, using optical character recognition. The apparatus may connect to a secondary device to transmit information to the secondary device, and may receive information relating to the selected programme from the secondary device.

Link information may be extracted from the audio-visual AV data of the selected programme using optical character recognition OCR. A secondary device, such as a smartphone or tablet PC, may be used to transmit and receive the information, and may receive further information from the internet. If the link is an embedded URL the secondary device may load that webpage or if it is a telephone number the device may dial or send a text message to that number. The system may be interactive during live TV broadcasts and the secondary device may provide an augmented reality effect using its integrated camera.

column13: A flow guide for directing a fluid flow across a surface of a device, the flow guide includes a locating arrangement for locating the device with respect to the flow guide such that the surface is disposed generally in a first plane defined along first and second mutually perpendicular directions. column12: Generating and displaying a computer generated image on a future pose of a real world object
column13: Methods and systems for displaying a computer generated image corresponding to the pose of a real-world object in a mixed reality system. The system may include of a head-mounted display (HMD) device, a magnetic track system and an optical system. Pose data detected by the two tracking systems can be synchronized by a timestamp that is embedded in an electromagnetic field transmitted by the magnetic tracking system. A processor may also be configured to calculate a future pose of the real world object based on a time offset based on the time needed by the HMD to calculate, buffer and generate display output and on data from the two tracking systems, such that the relative location of the computer generated image (CGI) corresponds with the actual location of the real-world object relative to the real world environment at the time the CGI actually appears in the display.

column12: Flow guide for cleaning the end surface of an endoscope
column13: A flow guide 2 for directing fluid across an end surface 4 of an endoscope 6, in particular, for cleaning the lens of a laparoscope. The guide includes a channel through which the fluid flows and an outlet 10 through which it exits. The fluid flows parallel to the endoscope as it travels along the guide until it reaches a chamber (42, fig. 4) where it is made to turn through approximately 110° before leaving the outlet. The guide may include limb guide surfaces 20 positioned at the outlet (see fig. 2) to help the fluid spread out over the end surface. The outlet is curved such that the opening at the centre is smaller than at the sides 12. The resulting convex shape of the outlet ensures that the fluid flows more quickly through the centre than at the sides. The velocity profile created by the outlet aides flow attachment to the limb surfaces and also causes flow divergence.

column12: Improvements in or relating to methods of forming vitreous enamel coatings on metal articles and to muffle furnaces for carrying out such methods
column13: 762,004. Vitreous enamelling. MAIN, Ltd., R. & A. April 25, 1955 [Jan. 25, 1954], No. 2221/54. Drawings to Specification. Class 56 [Also in Group XII] A method of forming a vitreous enamel coating on metal articles, particularly cast iron parts, consists in heating the articles coated with a frit mixture in a heated chamber such as a muffle furnace in an atmosphere largely free of moisture. The method is shown applied to a muffle furnace (see Group XII) supplied with preheated air having a moisture content of approximately 0.5 per cent. For a muffle capacity of approximately 300 cu. ft., the rate of air flow should be between 4,000- 10,000 cu. ft./hr. The prior annealing of cast iron articles may be dispensed with using the method according to the invention, the cleaned articles simply being sprayed with enamel slurry and dried in the usual way before firing.

column12: Batch automated blocking and record matching
column13: Batch, or “offline”, blocking takes a set of records and generates sets (or blocks, hence the name blocking) of potentially matching records for the entire set. The blocks of potential matches are then passed to a matching process to evaluate which records match. Applications include but are not limited to individual matching such as student identification, householding, business matching, supply chain matching, financial matching, news or text matching, and other applications.

column12: GENERATING AND DISPLAYING A COMPUTER GENERATED IMAGE ON A FUTURE POSE OF A REAL WORLD OBJECT
column13: Methods and systems for displaying a computer generated image corresponding to the pose of a real-world object in a mixed reality system. The system may include of a head-mounted display (HMD) device, a magnetic track system and an optical system. Pose data detected by the two tracking systems can be synchronized by a timestamp that is embedded in an electromagnetic field transmitted by the magnetic tracking system. A processor may also be configured to calculate a future pose of the real world object based on a time offset based on the time needed by the HMD to calculate, buffer and generate display output and on data from the two tracking systems, such that the relative location of the computer generated image (CGI) corresponds with the actual location of the real-world object relative to the real world environment at the time the CGI actually appears in the display.

column12: INTERMEDIATE FOR SYNTHESIS OF HETEROCYCLIC-CYCLIC AMINE DERIVATIVE
column13: PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To obtain a new compound useful as an intermediate of a heterocyclic- cyclic amine derivative as a cholinesterase suppressor and useful for improving remembering in a patient having dementia and Alzheimer's disease. SOLUTION: This intermediate is a compound expressed by formula I (R1 and R2 are each H, a 1-6C alkoxy, benzyloxy, phenoxy or the like; R7 and R8 are each H, a 1-6C alkyl, alkoxycarbonyl or the like; R11 is H or a nitrogen protecting group), e.g. 3- 2-[1-(phenylmethyl)-4-piperidinyl]ethyl-1,2-benzisoxazole maleate). The compound is obtained by subjecting a compound of formula II to deprotonation with a base such as 3-butyllithium in the presence of an alkylation agent of formula III in a polar aprotic solvent such as tetrahydrofuran at about -78 deg.C to about 30 deg.C, or thereafter adding an alkylation agent.

column13: In some examples, an additive manufacturing machine includes an unfocused energy source to heat portions of a layer of build material as the unfocused energy source moves across the layer of build material during a build operation of a three-dimensional (3D) object. A focused energy source is controllable to selectively direct focused energy on the layer of build material during the build operation.

column12: CELESTIAL POSITIONING SYSTEM AND METHOD
column13: In a method of determining the position of an object, raw image data of the sky is recorded using a celestial imaging unit. The last known position, orientation, date, and time data of the object are obtained, and the position of a celestial body is measured. A latitude and longitude of the object is determined by matching the measured celestial body position to the expected celestial body position based on the input parameters.
column15: AYCOCK TODD;;LOMPADO ARTHUR;;CHENAULT DAVID;;SMITH ADAM

column12: Flow guide for cleaning an endoscope
column13: A flow guide 2 for directing a fluid flow across a surface 4 of an endoscope 6. The flow guide 2 includes a locating arrangement for locating the device with respect to the flow guide 2 such that the surface 4 is disposed generally in a first plane defined along first and second mutually perpendicular directions, and a channel 8 for guiding the fluid flow, the channel 8 having sides spaced with respect to each other in the first direction. The flow guide 2 also includes a respective limb 18 extending from each of the sides generally in the second direction, each limb 18 defining a limb guide surface 20 extending generally in a third direction perpendicular to the first and second directions and being convex in a plane parallel to the first plane to cause fluid flow from the channel to diverge in the first direction as it flows across the surface 4 of the device.

column12: FLOW GUIDE
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a flow guide for changing the direction of a fluid flow so as to flow across the surface of a device to clean a lens on the spot without removing a laparoscope from a patient's abdominal cavity.

SOLUTION: The flow guide directs a fluid flow across a surface of a device, for example a lens surface of an endoscope, in a controlled manner to facilitate flow attachment to the surface. Embodiments include features that impart a non-uniform velocity profile and/or include guide surfaces for facilitating flow attachment and/or coverage.

column12: CELESTIAL POSITIONING SYSTEM AND METHOD
column13: In a method of determining the position of an object, raw image data of the sky is recorded using a celestial imaging unit. The last known position, orientation, date, and time data of the object are obtained, and the position of a celestial body is measured. A latitude and longitude of the object is determined by matching the measured celestial body position to the expected celestial body position based on the input parameters. A system for determining a new position of an object comprises a celestial imaging unit configured to record image data of the sky, a signal processing unit, and a signal processing unit configured to receive and store in memory the image data received from the celestial imaging unit. The signal processing unit filters the image to find the positions of celestial objects in the sky. The signal processing unit is further configured to use roll and pitch from an IMU, and date and time from a clock to determine the object's position (latitude and longitude).

column12: Batch automated blocking and record matching
column13: Batch, or “offline”, blocking takes a set of records and generates sets (or blocks, hence the name blocking) of potentially matching records for the entire set. The blocks of potential matches are then passed to a matching process to evaluate which records match. Applications include but are not limited to individual matching such as student identification, householding, business matching, supply chain matching, financial matching, news or text matching, and other applications.

column12: Generating and Displaying a Computer Generated Image on a Future Pose of a Real World Object
column13: Methods and systems for displaying a computer generated image corresponding to the pose of a real-world object in a mixed reality system. The system may include of a head-mounted display (HMD) device, a magnetic track system and an optical system. Pose data detected by the two tracking systems can be synchronized by a timestamp that is embedded in an electromagnetic field transmitted by the magnetic tracking system. A processor may also be configured to calculate a future pose of the real world object based on a time offset based on the time needed by the HMD to calculate, buffer and generate display output and on data from the two tracking systems, such that the relative location of the computer generated image (CGI) corresponds with the actual location of the real-world object relative to the real world environment at the time the CGI actually appears in the display.

column12: Thermal interface material and methods for assembling and operating devices using such material
column13: A tape for providing thermal contact between an energy generating device and a energy dissipating device is disclosed. The tape comprises a thermally conductive material configured to be adhesively coupled to one of the energy devices, and a tab. The first portion of the thermally conductive material can be separated from the tab by removal of the tab along a weakened interface. The tape may further comprise a sheet such as a sheet of aluminum foil. The weakened interface typically exists between two portions of the sheet or two portions of the thermally conductive material, but could exist anywhere. The weakened interface can be a perforated line. The weakened interface can also be formed along a straight line.

column12: APPARATUS AND SYSTEM FOR ARC ELIMINATION AND METHOD OF ASSEMBLY
column13: PURPOSE: An apparatus and system for eliminating an arc and an assembly method thereof are provided to eliminate an arc flash by improving the structure of an ablative plasma gun. CONSTITUTION: An ablative plasma gun(100) comprises a first part(106) having a first diameter(110) and a second part(108) having a second diameter(112) bigger than the first diameter. A chamber(104) is ruled by the first part and the second part. The second part is arranged at an upside of the first part. The first part and the second part are integrally formed. The ablative plasma gun further includes a first gun electrode(122) including a first end part(126) and a second gun electrode(124) including a second end part(128). The first end part and the second end part are extended to directions faced from a central axis line of the chamber.

column12: SYSTEMS FOR AND METHODS OF EXTENDING LIFETIME OF NON-VOLATILE MEMORY
column13: Systems and Methods are provided for increasing the number of writes to a page of non-volatile memory before the page must be erased. According to an embodiment, instead of writing a dataword directly to memory, a codeword is written to the memory location. The codeword is selected to minimize overwrite (e.g., bit-flipping) and to maximize the spread of wear across memory cells. In accordance with various embodiments of the invention, coset coding is integrated with error correction encoding; and once the previous state of a page is determined, a coset representative is selected on the basis of maximizing the number of writes to the page before erasing.

column12: Celestial positioning system and method
column13: In a method of determining the position of an object, raw image data of the sky is recorded using a celestial imaging unit. The last known position, orientation, date, and time data of the object are obtained, and the position of a celestial body is measured. A latitude and longitude of the object is determined by matching the measured celestial body position to the expected celestial body position based on the input parameters. A system for determining a new position of an object comprises a celestial imaging unit configured to record image data of the sky, a signal processing unit, and a signal processing unit configured to receive and store in memory the image data received from the celestial imaging unit. The signal processing unit filters the image to find the positions of celestial objects in the sky. The signal processing unit is further configured to use roll and pitch from an IMU, and date and time from a clock to determine the object's position (latitude and longitude).

column12: Klappenventilanordnung mit verbesserter Strömungscharakteristik
column13: Eine Steuerventilanordnung, die ein Klappenventil verwendet, das einen Ventilkörper und eine zwischen einer aufsitzenden Position und einer offenen Position bewegliche Ventilscheibe besitzt. Die Steuerventilanordnung umfasst einen Strömungseinsatz, der längs der Innenseite des Ventilkörpers positioniert und im Allgemeinen auf eine erste äußere Dichtungskante der drehbaren Ventilscheibe ausgerichtet ist. Der Strömungseinsatz hält einen engen Abstand zu der ersten äußeren Dichtungskante der Ventilscheibe aufrecht, wenn die Ventilscheibe sich anfänglich von dem Ventilsitz wegbewegt. Die Steuerventilanordnung kann auch einen ersten stromaufseitigen Klappenkäfig und einen zweiten stromabseitigen Klappenkäfig, die auf gegenüberliegenden Seiten des Ventilkörpers positioniert sind, umfassen. Der erste und der zweite Klappenkäfig unterstützen die Steuerung der Fluidströmung an der Ventilscheibe vorbei, wenn sich die Ventilscheibe aus ihrer aufsitzenden Position in ihre geöffnete Position bewegt.
column15: YEARY ARTHUR R;;ZMICK ADAM;;KIELAR AARON;;BARDELLI MATT

column12: QUADRATURE TRIM VERTICAL ELECTRODES FOR YAW AXIS CORIOLIS VIBRATORY GYROSCOPE
column13: Microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) yaw gyroscopes having out-of-plane quadrature trim electrodes are described. The gyroscope includes a proof mass configured to be driven in-plane. The proof mass includes an opening, or a plurality of openings. The out-of-plane quadrature trim electrodes are positioned to laterally overlap edges of the opening in a projection plane. The out-of-plane quadrature trim electrodes trim in-plane motion of the proof mass in one or two directions to limit quadrature motion. The out-of-plane quadrature trim electrodes may be arranged in a symmetric pattern to enable mode switching.

column12: BUTTERFLY VALVE EQUIPPED WITH IMPROVED FLOWING CHARACTERISTIC
column13:
PROBLEM TO BE SOLVED: To provide a system for giving additional controllability of a butterfly valve.

SOLUTION: A control valve assembly utilizes the butterfly valve having a valve body and a valve disc movable between a seated position and an open position. The control valve assembly includes a flow insert positioned along the interior of the valve body and generally aligned with a first outer sealing edge of the rotatable valve disc. The flow insert maintains close spacing to the first outer sealing edge of the valve disc as the valve disc initially moves away from the valve seat. The control valve assembly can also include a first upstream butterfly cage and a second downstream butterfly cage positioned on both sides of the valve body. The first and second butterfly cages aid in controlling the flow of fluid past the valve disc as the valve disc moves from its seated position to its open position.

column12: THERMAL INTERFACE MATERIAL AND METHODS FOR ASSEMBLING AND OPERATING DEVICES USING SUCH MATERIAL
column13: A tape for providing thermal contact between an energy generating device and a energy dissipating device is disclosed. The tape comprises a thermally conductive material configured to be adhesively coupled to one of the energy devices, and a tab. The first portion of the thermally conductive material can be separated from the tab by removal of the tab along a weakened interface. The tape may further comprise a sheet such as a sheet of aluminum foil. The weakened interface typically exists between two portions of the sheet or two portions of the thermally conductive material, but could exist anywhere. The weakened interface can be a perforated line. The weakened interface can also be formed along a straight line.

column12: Systems for and methods of extending lifetime of non-volatile memory
column13: Systems and Methods are provided for increasing the number of writes to a page of non-volatile memory before the page must be erased. According to an embodiment, instead of writing a dataword directly to memory, a codeword is written to the memory location. The codeword is selected to minimize overwrite (e.g., bit-flipping) and to maximize the spread of wear across memory cells. In accordance with various embodiments of the invention, coset coding is integrated with error correction encoding; and once the previous state of a page is determined, a coset representative is selected on the basis of maximizing the number of writes to the page before erasing.

column12: Butterfly valve assembly with improved flow characteristics
column13: A control valve assembly that utilizes a butterfly valve having a valve body and a valve disc movable between a seated position and an open position. The control valve assembly includes a flow insert positioned along the interior of the valve body and generally aligned with a first outer sealing edge of the rotatable valve disc. The flow insert maintains close spacing to the first outer sealing edge of the valve disc as the valve disc initially moves away from the valve seat. The control valve assembly can also include a first, upstream butterfly cage and a second, downstream butterfly cage positioned on opposite sides of the valve body. The first and second butterfly cages aid in controlling the flow of fluid past the valve disc as the valve disc moves from its seated position to its open position.

column12: Buckle assembly
column13: The present invention provides a buckle assembly which includes a first tongue, a second tongue, and a socket having a cavity for receiving at least a portion of the first tongue and second tongue. Each tongue includes a tongue coupling member which operates to register the first tongue and second tongue to be inserted into the socket simultaneously. Alternatively, the first tongue and second tongue may be inserted separately wherein the tongue coupling member allows the tongues to be slid relative to one another thereby facilitating individual insertion of the first tongue and the second tongue. In addition, the buckle assembly includes a securement member having a button on each tongue. Both the button on the first tongue and the button on the second tongue must be simultaneously actuated to eject the tongues from the socket. Further, the buckle assembly provides a first slot, a second slot, and a third slot configured to receive a corresponding belt. The slots are oriented relative to one another such that the buckle assembly operates as a five point restraint.

column12: THERMAL INTERFACE MATERIAL AND METHODS FOR ASSEMBLING AND OPERATING DEVICES USING SUCH MATERIAL
column13: A tape for providing thermal contact between an energy generating device and a energy dissipating device is disclosed. The tape comprises a thermally conductive material configured to be adhesively coupled to one of the energy devices, and a tab. The first portion of the thermally conductive material can be separated from the tab by removal of the tab along a weakened interface. The tape may further comprise a sheet such as a sheet of aluminum foil. The weakened interface typically exists between two portions of the sheet or two portions of the thermally conductive material, but could exist anywhere. The weakened interface can be a perforated line. The weakened interface can also be formed along a straight line.

column12: Aircraft Ceiling Resettable Decompression Roller Assembly
column13: A system and method for relieving pressure from a passenger cabin of an aircraft during a decompression event with a resettable decompression system. The system includes a resettable decompression retainer having a swing arm pivotably connected to a base. The swing arm has a bias relative to the base provided by a spring connected to both the swing arm and the base. The swing arm engages a slip fitting that is attached to a ceiling panel of the aircraft. The resettable decompression system allows the ceiling panel to move thus allowing air pressures between a passenger cabin and a crown space to equalize. After a decompression event, the resettable decompression retainer can be manually reset without the use of tools and without repairing or replacing the resettable decompression retainer.

column12: CONTROL OF GENE EXPRESSION IN PLANTS
column13: Chimeric insect hormone receptors and receptor cassettes are provided as well as methods for their use in regulating expression of target polypeptides in plants in the presence of appropriate chemical ligands. In particular, each receptor cassette encodes a receptor polypeptide that comprises a DNA binding domain, a hinge region, a ligand binding domain and an activation domain. According to one embodiment, the hinge and ligand binding domains are from two different insect ecdysone receptors. According to another embodiment, the receptor cassettes are chimeric in that one or more of the DNA binding or activation domains are obtained from a source heterologous with respect to the other domains present in the chimeric receptor cassette.

column12: Changing virtual items based on real-world events
column13: A method of changing virtual items based on real-world events is disclosed. It is detected that a player of a computer-implemented game has performed a location-based action. An attribute of a virtual item in an inventory of a player character in the computer-implemented game is changed based on the detecting that the player has performed the location-based action. The player character is controlled in the computer-implemented game by the player of the computer-implemented game and the virtual item is usable within the computer-implemented game by the player character.

column12: 플로우 배터리 내의 기생 반응의 경감
column13: 생산적인 전기화학 반응은 전기화학 셀을 2 개의 하프-셀로 나누는 세퍼레이터의 근처에서 가장 효과적으로 발생할 수 있다. 기생 반응은 세퍼레이터로부터 더 멀리 이격된 위치에서 종종 발생할 수 있다. 일반적으로 기생 반응은 플로우 배터리 및 기타 전기화학 시스템에서 바람직하지 않으며, 이는 작동 성능에 영향을 줄 수 있기 때문이다. 기생 반응의 발생이 감소된 플로우 배터리는 제 1 전극을 수용하는 제 1 하프-셀, 제 2 전극을 수용하는 제 2 하프-셀, 제 1 하프-셀과 제 2 하프-셀 사이에 배치되고, 제 1 전극 및 제 2 전극과 접촉하는 세퍼레이터, 제 1 전극과 접촉하는 제 1 바이폴라 플레이트, 제 2 전극과 접촉하는 제 2 바이폴라 플레이트를 포함할 수 있고, 제 1 전극의 일부 또는 제 1 바이폴라 플레이트는 유전체 재료를 포함한다. 제 1 전극 및 제 1 바이폴라 플레이트는 유전체 재료를 포함하는 경우에 연속하는 전기 전도 경로를 형성한다.

column12: Changing a virtual world based on real-world locations of players
column13: A method of changing a virtual world of a computer-implemented game based on real-world locations of players of the computer-implemented game is disclosed. A presence of a player of the computer-implemented game is detected at a physical location. A presence of an additional player of the computer-implemented game is detected at the physical location based on a communication received from the player of the computer-implemented game. An aspect of the virtual world of the computer-implemented game is changed based on the detecting of the presence of the player at the physical location and the detecting of the presence of the additional player of the computer-implemented game at the physical location.

column12: Changing a virtual world based on real-world locations of players
column13: A method of changing a virtual world of a computer-implemented game based on real-world locations of players of the computer-implemented game is disclosed. A presence of a player of the computer-implemented game is detected at a physical location. A presence of an additional player of the computer-implemented game is detected at the physical location based on a communication received from the player of the computer-implemented game. An aspect of the virtual world of the computer-implemented game is changed based on the detecting of the presence of the player at the physical location and the detecting of the presence of the additional player of the computer-implemented game at the physical location.

column12: CHANGING A VIRTUAL WORLD BASED ON REAL-WORLD LOCATIONS OF PLAYERS
column13: A method of changing a virtual world of a computer-implemented game based on real-world locations of players of the computer-implemented game is disclosed. A presence of a player of the computer-implemented game is detected at a physical location. A presence of an additional player of the computer-implemented game is detected at the physical location based on a communication received from the player of the computer-implemented game. An aspect of the virtual world of the computer-implemented game is changed based on the detecting of the presence of the player at the physical location and the detecting of the presence of the additional player of the computer-implemented game at the physical location.

column12: MITIGATION OF PARASITIC REACTIONS WITHIN FLOW BATTERIES
column13: Productive electrochemical reactions can often occur most effectively in proximity to a separator dividing an electrochemical cell into two half-cells. Parasitic reactions can often occur at locations more removed from the separator. Parasitic reactions are generally undesirable in flow batteries and other electrochemical systems, since they can impact operating performance. Flow batteries having a decreased incidence of parasitic reactions can include, a first half-cell containing a first electrode, a second half-cell containing a second electrode, a separator disposed between the first half-cell and the second half-cell and contacting the first and second electrodes, a first bipolar plate contacting the first electrode, and a second bipolar plate contacting the second electrode, where a portion of the first electrode or the first bipolar plate contains a dielectric material. The first electrode and the first bipolar plate still define a contiguous electrically conductive pathway when containing the dielectric material.

column12: Changing virtual items based on location-based actions
column13: A method of changing virtual items based on location-based actions is disclosed. It is detected that a player of a computer-implemented game has performed a location-based action. An attribute of a virtual item of the player of the computer-implemented game is changed based on the detecting that the player of the computer-implemented game has performed the location-based action.

column12: METHODS OF TREATING NEUROLOGICAL AUTOIMMUNE DISORDERS WITH CYCLOPHOSPHAMIDE
column13: Described herein are methods for treating neurological autoimmune disorders in which the treatment method includes administering an immunoablative agent to eliminate most or essentially all maturing and mature elements of the immune system in an affected individual. Following this step, the individual is administered agents to reestablish the ablated immune system.

column12: CHANGING A VIRTUAL WORLD BASED ON REAL-WORLD LOCATIONS OF PLAYERS
column13: A method of changing a virtual world of a computer-implemented game based on real-world locations of players of the computer-implemented game is disclosed. A presence of a player of the computer-implemented game is detected at a physical location. A presence of an additional player of the computer-implemented game is detected at the physical location based on a communication received from the player of the computer-implemented game. An aspect of the virtual world of the computer-implemented game is changed based on the detecting of the presence of the player at the physical location and the detecting of the presence of the additional player of the computer-implemented game at the physical location.
column15: ETTER NATHAN ARTHUR;;MONAHAN JAY;;OCKO MATTHEW ADAM;;REYNOLDS BRIAN

column12: Mitigation of parasitic reactions within flow batteries
column13: Productive electrochemical reactions can often occur most effectively in proximity to a separator dividing an electrochemical cell into two half-cells. Parasitic reactions can often occur at locations more removed from the separator. Parasitic reactions are generally undesirable in flow batteries and other electrochemical systems, since they can impact operating performance. Flow batteries having a decreased incidence of parasitic reactions can include, a first half-cell containing a first electrode, a second half-cell containing a second electrode, a separator disposed between the first half-cell and the second half-cell and contacting the first and second electrodes, a first bipolar plate contacting the first electrode, and a second bipolar plate contacting the second electrode, where a portion of the first electrode or the first bipolar plate contains a dielectric material. The first electrode and the first bipolar plate still define a contiguous electrically conductive pathway when containing the dielectric material.
column15: MORRIS-COHEN ADAM;;PURANAM SRIVATSAVA;;GOELTZ JOHN;;ESSWEIN ARTHUR J

column12: HARVESTING ENERGY DURING COMPRESSION OF A PILL PACK
column13: Various methods and apparatus disclosed herein relate to apparatus and techniques for harvesting energy from operation of a pill pack, and utilizing that energy for various purposes. In various embodiments, an energy harvesting apparatus configured to receive a pill pack (104, 304) is disclosed. An energy harvesting apparatus in accordance with various embodiment may include a housing (102, 302), where the housing is configured to receive a pill pack (104, 304), and an electrical generator incorporated into the housing (102, 302), where the electrical generator converts motion associated with compression of at least one blister (103 1-n , 303 1-n ) of the pill pack (104, 304) expelling one or more pills (105 1-n , 305 1-n ) from the pill pack into electrical energy, where the electrical energy is used to collect one or more data points associated with operation of the pill pack during the expelling of the one or more pills.
column15: JONES ADAM;;DELLIMORE KIRAN HAMILTON J;;GRÜTERICH MARTIN;;BOUWMAN ARTHUR

column12: CHANGING A VIRTUAL WORLD BASED ON REAL-WORLD LOCATIONS OF PLAYERS
column13: A method of changing a virtual world of a computer-implemented game based on real-world locations of players of the computer-implemented game is disclosed. A presence of a player of the computer-implemented game is detected at a physical location. A presence of an additional player of the computer-implemented game is detected at the physical location based on a communication received from the player of the computer-implemented game. An aspect of the virtual world of the computer-implemented game is changed based on the detecting of the presence of the player at the physical location and the detecting of the presence of the additional player of the computer-implemented game at the physical location.

column12: Improvements in and relating to Machines for Lasting Boots and Shoes.
column13: 29,387. Parsons, A., Morton, J. A., Wright, J. C., and Wright, B. Dec. 24. Lasting; cementing; soles.-Relates to an apparatus for wiping an upper over a last, and securing its edge to the insole. A framework A<1>, Fig. 1, supports a removable die or matrix B, which is lined with two sheets of india-rubber, a sole portion B', Fig. 7, extending right across the frame, and a heel portion B<2>, which is provided with an opening b<x> to receive the ankle portion of the last. The frame also carries resilient material at the part b<2>, to bear upon the waist portion of the last. The latter is positioned by a jack pin g, and is provided with a hook c, which is engaged by a treadle-rod c<1>. When the treadle is depressed, the last is forced into the die B, and the linings B', B<2> exercise a wiping action on the upper and draw it well over the last. The edges of the upper are then cemented and pressed down to the insole, for which purpose the apparatus is provided with wiper blades F, Fig. 4, pivoted together at f and to the frame A<1> at f<1>. The blades are arranged slightly below the plane of the insole, and have to be sprung upwards before they can be moved inwards. They may be formed with downward flanges f<3> for acting on the edge of the upper adjacent to the heel. The edges of the upper may be turned inwards instead of outwards. If an outer sole is to be applied, it is placed in a recess in a presser bar H, which is then forced downwards on to the prepared insole. In some cases, the sheets B', B<2> may consist of pneumatic cushions.

column12: Butterfly valve assembly with improved flow characteristics
column13: A control valve assembly that utilizes a butterfly valve having a valve body and a valve disc movable between a seated position and an open position. The control valve assembly includes a flow insert positioned along the interior of the valve body and generally aligned with a first outer sealing edge of the rotatable valve disc. The flow insert maintains close spacing to the first outer sealing edge of the valve disc as the valve disc initially moves away from the valve seat. The control valve assembly can also include a first, upstream butterfly cage and a second, downstream butterfly cage positioned on opposite sides of the valve body. The first and second butterfly cages aid in controlling the flow of fluid past the valve disc as the valve disc moves from its seated position to its open position.
